    "Radner (1986) showed that relaxing the strict notion of rationality (e.g., being satisfied by a 'close enough' payoff) allows for longer periods of cooperation.",
    "Kreps et al. (1982) demonstrated similar results on the basis that agents have incomplete information about the options, motivations, or behaviors of other players.",
    "A more interesting solution from a complexity perspective was provided by Neyman (1985), who showed that cooperation becomes an equilibrium if the players have sufficiently small memories."
